events.description: Some 15,000 starving Christian soldiers begin the siege of Jerusalem by marching in a religious procession around the city as its Muslim defenders watch.
events.html: • 1099 – Some 15,000 starving Christian soldiers begin the siege of Jerusalem by marching in a religious procession around the city as its Muslim defenders watch.

events.description: The Byzantines defeat the Hungarian army decisively at Sirmium, forcing the Hungarians to sue for peace.
events.html: • 1167 – The Byzantines defeat the Hungarian army decisively at Sirmium, forcing the Hungarians to sue for peace.[1]

events.description: Roger of Lauria, commanding the Aragonese fleet, defeats an Angevin fleet sent to put down a rebellion on Malta.
events.html: • 1283 – Roger of Lauria, commanding the Aragonese fleet, defeats an Angevin fleet sent to put down a rebellion on Malta.

events.description: Vasco da Gama sets sail on the first direct European voyage to India.
events.html: • 1497 – Vasco da Gama sets sail on the first direct European voyage to India.

events.description: Our Lady of Kazan, a holy icon of the Russian Orthodox Church, is discovered underground in the city of Kazan, Tatarstan.
events.html: • 1579 – Our Lady of Kazan, a holy icon of the Russian Orthodox Church, is discovered underground in the city of Kazan, Tatarstan.

events.description: Charles II of England grants John Clarke a Royal charter to Rhode Island.
events.html: • 1663 – Charles II of England grants John Clarke a Royal charter to Rhode Island.

events.description: Peter I of Russia defeats Charles XII of Sweden at the Battle of Poltava, thus effectively ending Sweden's status as a major power in Europe.
events.html: • 1709 – Peter I of Russia defeats Charles XII of Sweden at the Battle of Poltava, thus effectively ending Sweden's status as a major power in Europe.

events.description: The Battle of Dynekilen forces Sweden to abandon its invasion of Norway.
events.html: • 1716 – The Battle of Dynekilen forces Sweden to abandon its invasion of Norway.

events.description: An estimated magnitude 8.7 earthquake causes a tsunami that damages more than 1,000 km (620 mi) of Chile's coastline.
events.html: • 1730 – An estimated magnitude 8.7 earthquake causes a tsunami that damages more than 1,000 km (620 mi) of Chile's coastline.

events.description: Reverend Jonathan Edwards preaches to his congregation in Enfield, Connecticut his most famous sermon, "Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God"; an influence for the First Great Awakening.
events.html: • 1741 – Reverend Jonathan Edwards preaches to his congregation in Enfield, Connecticut his most famous sermon, "Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God"; an influence for the First Great Awakening.[2]

entities.name: Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God

events.description: French forces hold Fort Carillon against the British at Ticonderoga, New York.
events.html: • 1758 – French forces hold Fort Carillon against the British at Ticonderoga, New York.

events.description: British forces defeat French forces in the last naval battle in New France.
events.html: • 1760 – British forces defeat French forces in the last naval battle in New France.

events.description: The Olive Branch Petition is signed by the Continental Congress of the Thirteen Colonies of North America.
events.html: • 1775 – The Olive Branch Petition is signed by the Continental Congress of the Thirteen Colonies of North America.

events.description: Church bells (possibly including the Liberty Bell) are rung after John Nixon delivers the first public reading of the Declaration of Independence of the United States.
events.html: • 1776 – Church bells (possibly including the Liberty Bell) are rung after John Nixon delivers the first public reading of the Declaration of Independence of the United States.

entities.name: Declaration of Independence of the United States

events.description: Promulgation of the Bayonne Statute, a royal charter Joseph Bonaparte intended as the basis for his rule as king of Spain.
events.html: • 1808 – Promulgation of the Bayonne Statute, a royal charter Joseph Bonaparte intended as the basis for his rule as king of Spain.

events.description: Chippewas turn over a huge tract of land in Ontario to the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1822 – Chippewas turn over a huge tract of land in Ontario to the United Kingdom.

events.description: The Perry Expedition arrives in Edo Bay with a treaty requesting trade.
events.html: • 1853 – The Perry Expedition arrives in Edo Bay with a treaty requesting trade.

events.description: King Charles XV & IV accedes to the throne of Sweden–Norway.
events.html: • 1859 – King Charles XV & IV accedes to the throne of Sweden–Norway.

events.description: Ikedaya Incident: The Choshu Han shishi's planned Shinsengumi sabotage on Kyoto, Japan at Ikedaya.
events.html: • 1864 – Ikedaya Incident: The Choshu Han shishi's planned Shinsengumi sabotage on Kyoto, Japan at Ikedaya.

events.description: The Mounties begin their March West.
events.html: • 1874 – The Mounties begin their March West.

events.description: The Hamburg massacre prior to the 1876 United States presidential election results in the deaths of six African-Americans of the Republican Party, along with one white assailant.
events.html: • 1876 – The Hamburg massacre prior to the 1876 United States presidential election results in the deaths of six African-Americans of the Republican Party, along with one white assailant.

events.description: Sailing ship USS Jeannette departs San Francisco carrying an ill-fated expedition to the North Pole.
events.html: • 1879 – Sailing ship USS Jeannette departs San Francisco carrying an ill-fated expedition to the North Pole.

events.description: The first issue of The Wall Street Journal is published.
events.html: • 1889 – The first issue of The Wall Street Journal is published.

events.description: St. John's, Newfoundland is devastated in the Great Fire of 1892.
events.html: • 1892 – St. John's, Newfoundland is devastated in the Great Fire of 1892.

events.description: The death of crime boss Soapy Smith, killed in the Shootout on Juneau Wharf, releases Skagway, Alaska from his iron grip.
events.html: • 1898 – The death of crime boss Soapy Smith, killed in the Shootout on Juneau Wharf, releases Skagway, Alaska from his iron grip.

events.description: Henrique Mitchell de Paiva Couceiro leads an unsuccessful royalist attack against the First Portuguese Republic in Chaves.
events.html: • 1912 – Henrique Mitchell de Paiva Couceiro leads an unsuccessful royalist attack against the First Portuguese Republic in Chaves.

events.description: The Dow Jones Industrial Average reaches its lowest level of the Great Depression, closing at 41.22.
events.html: • 1932 – The Dow Jones Industrial Average reaches its lowest level of the Great Depression, closing at 41.22.

events.description: The first rugby union test match between the Wallabies of Australia and the Springboks of South Africa is played at Newlands Stadium in Cape Town.

events.description: Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Afghanistan sign the Treaty of Saadabad.
events.html: • 1937 – Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Afghanistan sign the Treaty of Saadabad.

events.description: Reports are broadcast that a UFO crash-landed in Roswell, New Mexico in what became known as the Roswell UFO incident.
events.html: • 1947 – Reports are broadcast that a UFO crash-landed in Roswell, New Mexico in what became known as the Roswell UFO incident.

events.description: The United States Air Force accepts its first female recruits into a program called the Women's Air Force (WAF).
events.html: • 1948 – The United States Air Force accepts its first female recruits into a program called the Women's Air Force (WAF).

events.description: Francis Gary Powers is charged with espionage resulting from his flight over the Soviet Union.
events.html: • 1960 – Francis Gary Powers is charged with espionage resulting from his flight over the Soviet Union.

events.description: Ne Win besieges and blows up the Rangoon University Student Union building to crush the Student Movement.
events.html: • 1962 – Ne Win besieges and blows up the Rangoon University Student Union building to crush the Student Movement.

events.description: Canadian Pacific Air Lines Flight 21 is destroyed by a bomb near 100 Mile House, Canada, killing 52.
events.html: • 1965 – Canadian Pacific Air Lines Flight 21 is destroyed by a bomb near 100 Mile House, Canada, killing 52.[3]

events.description: King Mwambutsa IV Bangiriceng of Burundi is deposed by his son Prince Charles Ndizi.
events.html: • 1966 – King Mwambutsa IV Bangiriceng of Burundi is deposed by his son Prince Charles Ndizi.

events.description: The Chrysler wildcat strike begins in Detroit, Michigan.
events.html: • 1968 – The Chrysler wildcat strike begins in Detroit, Michigan.

events.description: Richard Nixon delivers a special congressional message enunciating Native American self-determination as official US Indian policy, leading to the Indian Self-Determination and Education Assistance Act of 1975.

events.html: • 1972 – Israeli Mossad assassinate Palestinian writer Ghassan Kanafani.

events.html: • 1980 – The inaugural 1980 State of Origin game is won by Queensland who defeat New South Wales 20–10 at Lang Park.

events.description: Aeroflot Flight 4225 crashes near Almaty International Airport in the then Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic (present day Kazakhstan) killing all 166 people on board.

events.html: • 1982 – A failed assassination attempt against Iraqi president Saddam Hussein results in the Dujail Massacre over the next several months.
